<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-702-473  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 702 473.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  Dec 17, 1990 v5 n125 p21(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lawsuit settlement: ATandamp;T in out-of-court settlement with MCI onlawsuits involving telemarketing andamp; advertising. (MCICommunications Corp.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Cases)MCI Communications Corp. (Cases).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     Telephone CompaniesLegal IssuesCourt CasesTelemarketingAdvertising.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ATandamp;T Wednesday announced it has reached an out-of-court settlement with MCIon lawsuits involving telemarketing and advertising.andM;Terms of the settlement were not disclosed.andM;The two firms will propose to the FCC safeguards to protect consumers againstbeing switched to a long distance carrier without their permission.andM;&quot;Today's settlement will help put control of the long distance buyingdecision back where it belongs, in the hands of consumers,&quot; said Robert J.andO;Ranalli, ATandamp;T's president of consumer communications services.andM;The proposed safeguards would require that at least one of the followingactions take place before a consumer's long distance service is switched:andM;o  Consumer signs an authorization card and sends it to the long distancecarrier;andM;o Consumer initiates a call to the local telephone company or the longdistance carrier;andM;o Consumer initiates a call from home to an automated 800 number, and througha sequence of prompts, confirms the choice of long distance carrier; orandM;o Consumer's choice of a long distance carrier is verified by someone from anindependent firm unaffiliated with any long distance carrier.andM;In October, 1989, MCI and ATandamp;T filed legal claims against each other,alleging false and deceptive advertising.andP;  On January 10, 1990, ATandamp;T sued MCIfor false and deceptive telemarketing practices.andP;  (SEE EDGE, 10/89 andamp; 1/90)andM;US SPRINT RESPONDS TO ATandamp;T'S andamp; MCI'S PROPOSALS TO CURB &quot;SLAMMING&quot; Uponknowlege of the settlement, US Sprint issued the following statement:andM;&quot;US Sprint's primary concern is, and always will be, the customer.andM;&quot;Because of this concern, we are deeply committed to working to resolve the'slamming' issue.andP;  We initiated proposals for protective measures to the FCCback in March and again in October and, in fact, we have reviewed andtightened our procedures and safeguards.andM;&quot;Our proposed standards to the FCC include mandatory, minimum disclosures insolicitations, monitoring of telemarketing calls, 100 percent verification oftelemarketing calls, auditing by an independent firm, free and convenientreturn to previous carrier in cases of errors, and LEC cooperation intelemarketing sales.andM;&quot;The proposals made today by ATandamp;T and MCI appear to be an effort on theirpart to also safeguard against unauthorized switches.andP;  Sprint pledges to workclosely with the other carriers to see that the customer's best interests arekept in mind.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>